         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">4/8/81. ¶  ¶ As you probably now, dear Sir Joseph, are passing the sheets of the Monocotyledoneae for the generic work ¶  through the press, it may be well to mention to you, that the Nipa, which has ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">81.08.04</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, London, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81. f. 314.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">MS annotation by Hooker:</seg> [from] [Muller] with o[ne] seed of Helicia praealta quite dead. (to Museum) Thanked Septr 27/81. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Letter not found, </seg>
                     <seg style="color: #000000; font-style: italic; ">but see J. Hooker to M, 25 September 1881</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #000000; ">.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>4/8/81.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As you probably now, dear Sir Joseph, are passing the sheets of the <name key="Monocotyledoneae">Monocotyledoneae</name> for the generic work<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862–83).</p>
               </note> through the press, it may be well to mention to you, that the Nipa, which has been found on two places in Queensland is in no way different from N. fruticans though Mr Bailey gave it a new name.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="color: #000000; font-style: italic; ">MS annotation by Hooker in margin adjacent to this paragraph</seg>
                     <seg style="color: #000000; ">: noted.</seg>
                  </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M discussed <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Nipa%20fruticans">Nipa fruticans</name>
                     </seg> in B81.08.03, p. 127 where he credited Bailey with sending him specimens collected by Neame, but did not mention any new name Bailey had coined. Bailey did not publish until much later (Bailey (1889a)) a description of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">N. fruticans</seg> var <seg style="font-style: italic; ">neameana</seg> that he claimed to have recognised in 1881 'if not as a fresh species, as a marked form of the already known species'.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope, that you admit no petals in Orchids, <name key="Irideae">Irideae</name>, <name key="Liliaceae">Liliaceae</name> &amp;c; for if you do, then unavoidably they must also be acknowledged in <name key="Junceae">Junceae</name>, <name key="Resticaeae">Resticaeae</name> &amp;c</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
